Al-Noor Ramji, BT, CIO 100 2008 | CIO UK














































































































Al-Noor RamjiBTCIO 100 2008 - No. 4









Share

Twitter
Facebook
LinkedIn
Google Plus










Name:Al-Noor Ramji
Company:BT




In the last year, BT has embarked on a worldwide, group-wide transformation programme that has seen the creation of two new operating units: BT Design and BT Operate  (in-life operation).
Al-Noor Ramji, BT Design chief executive said his division is responsible for IT, networks, process and product design across BT, working with all lines of business to deliver products and services for the group’s customers in 170 around the globe.
“In addition, I am responsible as a member of the BT operating committee for 21CN [21st century network] – our open, global, real-time IP [internet protocol] platform and customer experience strategy across the group,” he said. “This broad remit has led MIT [Massachusetts Institute of Technology] to recently name me as an example of a new job title they have coined, chief strategic execution officer.”
Better-than-expected sales at BT for the first three months of 2008 boosted the company outlook, as its chief executive Ben Veerwayen prepared to step down after six years. The group reported an 18 per cent decline in pre-tax profits to £494 million over the first quarter of 2008. But excluding costs incurred from restructuring its business, BT earnings were up two per cent to £1.57 billion. “We have finished the year in style with a strong fourth quarter performance,” said Veerwayen. “BT is in great shape.”
Ramji’s view of his division’s greatest accomplishments support the fact that IT has an integral role to play in the telecommunication services giant’s business. “In the last year, these include building this new, converged organisation,” he said. “To the best of our knowledge, we are the first telco to be without a dedicated networks department. The convergence of four teams is leading to increases in speed of delivery, reduced costs, reduced complexity and increased control and capabilities for our customers. We have also met the tipping point in the realisation our platform strategy. Our matrix architecture now includes 22 strategic platforms over which we are exposing 160 re-usable capabilities via our Web21CN SDK  [software development kit].
“Over the next 12 months we will work to simplify and speed up the way we work, to ensure that we were are delivering right first time, every time for our customers. Specifically, we are capitalising on our success in end-to-end customer experience; testing to build, end-to-end customer experience monitoring; bringing together all the elements (networks, IT, process) to create proactive fault resolution; and more importantly, complete transparency to the customer via a shared portal,” he added.







Related












1 Report accuses BT of supplying backdoors for GCHQ and NSA







2 The Value of CIO collaboration in complex category management







3 Square Register turns an iPad into a cash register






In support of these initiatives and its end-to-end customer experience monitoring initiative in particular, BT Design will be implementing cloud services and operational and business support systems (OSS/BSS) transformation. “We are actively working to streamline and rationalise our systems and network estate to reflect our matrix architecture. To date we have achieved closure of over 1,300 systems,” said Ramji. BT is also working towards a more partnership-based model with its resource suppliers to ensure that they have shared objectives, with financial incentives and consequences, to meet customer experience metrics.
The organisation anticipates its technology implementations for the next year will deliver new revenues and lower costs. To this end, Ramji noted: “Specifically we are focused on faster development and assembly of new services, lower development operations and bid costs, reuse of investment and development and zero-touch provisioning.”
In industry terms, BT continues to operate in a sector challenged by compliance, security, enterprise resource planning (ERP) and systems consolidation and integration. In response, Ramji concluded: “Our challenges and opportunities remain technology performance and cost, including infrastructure virtualisation, network capacity, software complexity, managing customer demand, providing utility level service and on-demand, high speed comms, equivalence in the UK market and lifting of redundant regulation to facilitate new business models for open innovation, collaboration and development and new revenue models.”


